**DASH vs HLS:**
- HLS: Apple standard, required for iOS Safari, TS segments
- DASH: open standard, MP4 segments, better codec flexibility
- Netflix uses both: DASH for most devices, HLS for Apple

**Encoding for ABR:**
```
Each quality level: same duration segments (typically 2-6s)
Keyframe alignment: all renditions have I-frames at same timestamps
→ Allows seamless mid-segment quality switch

Video codec: H.264 (compatibility) → VP9 (30% better compression) → AV1 (50% better)
Audio: AAC → Opus
Containers: TS (HLS legacy) → fMP4 (modern, CMAF)
```

**Netflix-Specific:** Netflix pre-encodes each title at 10-20 bitrate/resolution combinations. Their per-title encoding (not per-resolution) optimizes bits for each scene — action scenes get more bits; static scenes get fewer. 20% bandwidth savings vs. fixed per-resolution encoding.

Chaos Monkey (Netflix) randomly terminates production instances to verify that systems can withstand failures gracefully. The broader Simian Army tests different failure scenarios.

**Philosophy:** "Hope is not a strategy" — deliberately inject failures to find weaknesses before they happen naturally.

**Chaos Engineering Principles:**
1. Define steady-state (what normal looks like: error rate, latency, throughput)
2. Hypothesize that steady state continues during chaos
3. Introduce chaos (terminate instances, increase latency, corrupt data)
4. Look for differences — if steady state holds, confidence increases
5. Run in production (or production-like staging)

**Architecture:**
```
Chaos Controller (schedule + rules)
         ↓
    Chaos Agents (run on target infrastructure)
    ├─ InstanceChaos: terminate EC2/K8s pods
    ├─ NetworkChaos: inject latency, packet loss, partition
    ├─ DiskChaos: fill disk, cause I/O errors
    └─ ClockChaos: NTP skew, time jumps
         ↓
    Observability Layer
    (Prometheus, Grafana, alert on SLA breach)
         ↓
    Auto-Rollback (if blast radius exceeded)
```

**Chaos Controller (Java):**
```java
@Service
public class ChaosMonkey {
    @Scheduled(cron = "0 0 9-17 * * MON-FRI") // business hours only
    public void runChaos() {
        if (!chaosConfig.isEnabled()) return;

        List<ServiceInstance> instances = serviceDiscovery.getAllInstances();

        // Exclude critical instances and recently-replaced ones
        List<ServiceInstance> candidates = instances.stream()
            .filter(i -> !i.hasTag("chaos-exempt"))
            .filter(i -> i.getAge().toHours() > 1) // warm instances only
            .filter(i -> instances.stream()
                .filter(o -> o.getServiceName().equals(i.getServiceName()))
                .count() > 1) // never kill last instance of a service
            .collect(Collectors.toList());

        if (candidates.isEmpty()) return;

        // Random selection
        ServiceInstance victim = candidates.get(
            ThreadLocalRandom.current().nextInt(candidates.size()));

        log.info("Chaos Monkey terminating: {}", victim.getId());
        terminateInstance(victim);
        metricsService.recordChaosEvent(victim);
    }

    private void terminateInstance(ServiceInstance instance) {
        if (instance.isK8sPod()) {
            k8sClient.pods().inNamespace(instance.getNamespace())
                     .withName(instance.getName()).delete();
        } else {
            ec2Client.terminateInstances(instance.getEc2InstanceId());
        }
    }
}
```

